HEADWORD: Ostiary
<hw>Os"ti*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>-ries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>ostium</ets> door,
entrance. See <er>Usher</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The mouth of a
river; an estuary.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who keeps the door, especially the door of a
church; a porter.</def> <rj><au>N. Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ostic</ent>⟦br⟧
